## SECTION 1 — Linux Core Commands

### Navigation
| Command | What it does | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `pwd` | Print working directory — shows where you are | `pwd` → `/home/bandit3` |
| `cd` | Change directory | `cd inhere` or `cd /home/ubuntu/Documents` |
| `cd -` | Go back to previous directory | `cd -` |
| `ls` | List files in current directory | `ls` |
| `ls -l` | Long/details view — shows permissions, size, owner | `ls -l` |
| `ls -a` | Show ALL files including hidden ones (dot files) | `ls -a` |
| `ls -la` | Long view + all files combined | `ls -la` |

> **Key insight:** On Linux, any file starting with `.` is hidden. `ls` won't show it. `ls -a` will.

---

### Reading Files
| Command | What it does | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `cat` | Read and print file contents | `cat readme` |
| `cat` with path | Read file without navigating to it | `cat /home/ubuntu/Documents/todo.txt` |
| `cat ./-filename` | Read file with dash in name — needs `./` prefix | `cat ./-file07` |
| `echo` | Output any text you provide | `echo "hello world"` |

> **Key insight:** The `./` prefix is critical when filenames start with a dash. Without it, Linux thinks the dash means you're passing a flag (like `-l` or `-a`), not a filename.

