### find Command Deep Dive
`find` is one of the most powerful commands in Linux. Add flags to filter results.

```bash
find [WHERE TO SEARCH] [FLAGS]
```

| Flag | What it means | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `./inhere` | Search inside this specific folder | `find ./inhere` |
| `-type f` | Only return regular files (not directories/symlinks) | `-type f` |
| `-size 1033c` | Only files exactly 1033 bytes (`c` = bytes) | `-size 1033c` |
| `! -executable` | NOT executable — plain text/data files only | `! -executable` |
| `-name "*.txt"` | Find files by name pattern | `-name "*.txt"` |

**Full example from Bandit Level 5:**
```bash
find ./inhere -type f -size 1033c ! -executable
```
Plain English: "Search inside inhere, find only regular files, exactly 1033 bytes, that can't be run as a program."

> **Real-world use:** In a real security engagement you'd use `find` to hunt for sensitive files on a compromised system — private keys, config files, credentials, backups.

---

### File Type Detection
```bash
file ./*
```
Runs type detection on every file in the current directory at once.

| Output | Means |
|---|---|
| `data` | Binary — not human-readable |
| `ASCII text` | Human-readable text |
| `executable` | Can be run as a program |
| `symbolic link` | Pointer to another file |

> **Key insight:** `./` handles the tricky dash-prefixed filenames. `*` means "everything."

